    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1947-09-15T22:30:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1947-09-15T22:30:00-05:00" n="48"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d48">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">711.45C21/9–1647: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Rangoon</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Packer</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">restricted</hi>
                        <lb/>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">immediate</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Rangoon</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1947-09-16T10:00:00+06:30"
                            >September 16, 1947—10 a.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>780. Received letter from So Nyun, Acting Secretary, Department Foreign Affairs,
                    dated September 12, reading as follows (abbreviated verbatim text): <pb
                        facs="0057" n="43" xml:id="pg_43"/>
                    <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“In reply your letter June 5, am directed ask you convey United States
                            Government agreement Government of Burma remove in due course present
                            limits consular district United States Consul General Rangoon. Formal
                            action achieve that purpose will not however be taken till agreement is
                            reached on text consular convention between two Governments.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <p>See my despatch 365, June 14.<note n="6" xml:id="d48fn6">Not printed, but see
                        telegram 486, June 14, from Rangoon, <ref target="#pg_32">p.
                        32</ref>.</note> While I consider this reply somewhat ungraciously phrased,
                    I recommend Department accept it as satisfactory in view all circumstances.<note
                        n="7" xml:id="d48fn7">Mr. Packer explained in telegram 4, September 19, 1
                        p.m., that he was told the Burmese “intend give us what we asked for”.
                        (711.45C21/9–1947)</note>
                </p>
                <p>If Department approves, I will now present text (Department’s instruction June
                    20) proposed consular convention urging prompt action.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Packer</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
